STORY:
**I. The Ashen Origin**

Jose Lanz stood on the precipice of the Seville Spire, the year 2150 washing over him in waves of radioactive smog and genetic despair. His body was a monument to failure—two hundred twenty centimeters of malnourished elegance, stretched too tall by the hunger genes that had been stitched into humanity’s threadbare DNA three centuries prior. His skin, inherited from a lineage of Spanish-Jewish exiles who had fled the Digital Inquisition only to be caught in the Climate Fracturing, held the ghost of olive—faded now to a mottled grey-yellow, like old parchment left in smoke. His hair, once the dark cascade of Moorish ancestry, had been thinned by pollution and reprogrammed to absorb sunlight inefficiently, standing in greasy spikes atop his skull. His left hand was a prosthetic of matte-black polymer and servomotor whine, grafted after the riot in 2148 when a genetic purity mob had torn his flesh away, mistaking his augmented nerves for terrorist tech.

But it was his eyes that defined him—milky, radiation-clouded, modified in childhood to see through the perpetual twilight of 2150’s atmosphere. They saw everything and absorbed nothing, reflecting only the hollow ache of a world that had forgotten how to hope.

Below him sprawled New Seville, a necropolis of poly-carbon domes where humanity huddled like terrified insects beneath the genetic plague they called *The Soulless Rot*. It was not a virus of flesh but of meaning—a creeping apathy that turned mothers into statues in their nurseries, caused children to stop breathing not from disease but from deciding that breath served no logical purpose. In 2150, belief was extinction. To believe in tomorrow was to invite death. And the source of this rot, Jose had discovered in the digital archives of the Dead Library, was a single text written in the year 1000 AD.

*A treatise by a monk named Lupus of San Millán,* the database had whispered through his neural implant. *It argued that God was not dead, but absent—a concept so devastating to the human mind that it triggered a chain-reaction of existential collapse, culminating in the Great Forgetting and our current state.*

Jose would go back. He would kill the monk before his quill touched parchment. He would save humanity from its own salvation, ironically enough.

**II. The Descent**

The Travel was not a machine; it was a cellular unmaking. Jose lay in the Chrono-Cell, suspended in ionic gel that ate his bio-rhythm and spun it backward. He felt his bones liquefy, then reform in the wrong order; he tasted the iron of his own blood as it un-spilled from wounds that had not yet happened. This was the paradox of time: to go backward, you had to cease to be forward.

Pain was the price of causality violation. Jose screamed, but sound had no direction in the Chrono-Cell—only pressure, only the sensation of his soul being pulled through a keyhole not meant for flesh. He saw flashes: his mother’s face dissolving into binary code, the Seville Spire collapsing upward, the year 1000 arriving not as a place but as a taste—*copper and beeswax and dust.*

Then, impact.

**III. The Year 1000**

Jose opened his eyes to a sky that made him weep. It was not the bruised ochre of 2150, but a violent, impossible azure—so blue it hurt his radiation-adapted eyes, so clear that birds looked like sutured ink-stitches against it. He lay in the mud of La Rioja, Spain, the year 1000 AD according to his wrist-comp’s desperate calculations.

He sat up, and the mud smelled of *real* earth—loam, decayed oak leaves, the faint ammoniac tang of unwashed sheep. His cybernetic left hand sputtered; the 2150 atmospheric filters it required were absent. Without them, the servos corroded within minutes, leaving him with a limp, dead appendage that he had to drag like a dead bird.

He was in a valley of impossible green. The monastery of San Millán de la Cogolla lay ahead, not the automated dome he expected, but a fortress of volcanic stone and timber, buttressed against the Pyrenees. Smoke rose from chimneys—real smoke, not filtered exhaust. People walked outside without face-masks or genetic shields. They spoke in a guttural Old Spanish that his implant struggled to parse, their words carrying the weight of centuries not yet lived.

Jose pulled his environmental suit tighter—a shimmering membrane that hid his mutations from the 1000 AD eye. He looked like a beggar with strange clothes, which was fortunate; in 1000 AD, being *too* perfect invited execution.

He moved toward the monastery using his remaining flesh-hand to pull himself along, his body twitching with withdrawal from the artificial endorphins of 2150. His muscles screamed; he had not felt gravity this heavy in generations. The air tasted of woodsmoke, unfiltered CO2 from the cookfires, and something darker—*fear.*

**IV. The Heresy**

Inside the monastery, the world was candlelight and stone. Jose moved like a ghost through the cloisters, his dead left hand trailing in the dust. He was looking for Lupus, and the monks knew him by description—stout of build, hair whitened early from candle-smoke inhalation, a spine curved like an interrogation stick from years of copying manuscripts in a bent posture.

He found him in the scriptorium, hunched over a desk of dark oak, a quill hovering above vellum. The monk looked up, and Jose stopped breathing.

Lupus was not writing heresy.

The monks had lied to the archives, or rather, the archives of 2150 had been corrupted by *The Soulless Rot* itself. The manuscript before Lupus was not a text of nihilism, but a prayer—a desperate, beautiful invocation to God asking for the strength to survive the coming darkness. It was a *shield*, not a weapon.

But Jose saw only what he needed to see. The 2150 mind was a scarred thing, incapable of recognizing hope when it wore the face of parchment and ink. He interpreted Lupus’s prayers as codes, his hope as mathematical proof of divine absence—*the very thing he had come to destroy.*

“*Dominus vobiscum,*” Lupus whispered, his Latin pure and resonant. *The Lord be with you.*

Jose’s implant translated: *[ERROR: NO GOD DETECTED]*.

**V. The Transgression**

Jose reached for his kinetic dart—the only weapon that had survived the Travel, a needle of ferro-glass that could pierce flesh and vaporize internally. He raised his right hand—flesh, warm, trembling with the terror of a man who had seen the end and thought he was the cure.

Lupus did not flinch. He looked at Jose’s milky eyes, his grey-yellow skin, the dead blackness of his polymer arm. The monk smiled—a terrible, sorrowful thing.

“You are the child I pray for,” Lupus said in Old Spanish, his eyes knowing and ancient. “You are the future that needs me to die.”

*No,* Jose thought, but his fingers had already fired. The dart struck Lupus in the throat with the sound of a snapped thread.

The monk fell, but not before his hands closed around Jose’s wrist—warm fingers against polymer and flesh. Blood sprayed, bright red as 2150 had forgotten blood could be. It did not smell of rust and chemicals, but of iron and life-ending sweetness.

“*Ave, Maria,*” the dying monk whispered. *Hail, Mary.* Not a curse. A blessing.

**VI. The Contamination**

Jose fled into the night, the monastery bells tolling for the dead monk. But he did not realize what had happened in his panic. As he fled, his 2150 blood—carrying the dormant *Soulless Rot* pathogen, the genetic memory of apathy and despair—had dripped from a wound on his side onto the manuscript Lupus had been writing.

The monks found the bloodstained page hours later. It was not heretical text, but prayer—and yet, stained with the blood of a martyr killed by a future demon. The monks believed this was holy: a sign that the end was coming, and they must preserve the *original* message.

They placed the manuscript in wax-filled lead boxes, sealing it against decay. But wax preserves pathogen spores for centuries. Wax does not kill the genetic memory of *The Soulless Rot.*

In 1050, a monk in another monastery would copy the page. The spores would become airborne dust, entering his lungs, mutating through six more centuries of copyists.

In 1492, the text would be translated into Hebrew and Arabic during the Inquisition’s flight.

In 1800, a scientist would study the “holy stain” under a primitive microscope and inspire the industrial revolution that would burn the world.

In 2150, humanity would crawl from the ashes believing they had lost God—not because Lupus had written a treatise of absence, but because Jose Lanz’s blood had carried the *idea* of absence into a time that did not know it, where it could spread like infection until belief became impossible.

**VII. The Return**

Jose awoke in the Chrono-Cell, gasping 2150 air—filtered, recycled, tasting of metal. His left hand was again functional, grafted with spare parts from the future. The year 2150 stretched before him in its familiar, terrible glory: ash-storms outside the dome, genetic mutations in the streets, the *Soulless Rot* sweeping through sectors like a plague of silence.

He had done it. He had killed the heretic. Why was 2150 unchanged?

He ran to the Dead Library, his cybernetic hand blazing through security protocols. He accessed the historical files on *Lupus of San Millán*.

The screen flickered. A new entry had appeared—*not from 2150, but from the year 1000 AD.* A digital reconstruction of wax-sealed manuscripts discovered in modern archaeological digs.

*“The Lupus Codex,”* the file read. *“Dating to c. 1000 AD, discovered in La Rioja in the 21st Century post-Collapse. Contains biological traces of unknown origin—genetic material matching no known human lineage from the Common Era.”*

Jose’s blood ran cold. He zoomed in on the high-resolution scan of the manuscript page.

There, in vivid chemical reconstruction, was a bloodstain. And beside it, written in 2150 script by the archaeologists who had found it: *Subject L-7’s DNA matches 99.8% with Jose Lanz, Seville Spire.*

He was staring at his own blood, preserved in 1000 AD wax. His blood that had infected the timeline.

**VIII. The Paradox**

The truth hit him like a physical blow, knocking him to his knees in the ash-gray light of 2150.

He had not traveled back to fix a mistake. He had traveled back *to create the mistake.*

The *Soulless Rot* of 2150 was not caused by a heretical treatise. It was caused by *him.* By his 2150 genetic material—mutated, desperate, carrying the DNA of despair and apocalypse—contaminating a pure moment in 1000 AD. A moment that, without his interference, would have produced a different future: one where Lupus’s prayer spread instead of poison.

The monks had preserved the bloodstained page as sacred relic, believing it to be holy martyrdom. They had venerated it for centuries. Each copyist who touched the page, each person who breathed the dust from its storage vaults... they had been inoculated with Jose’s apathy.

The *Soulless Rot* was not a plague from the past invading the future. It was Jose Lanz’s own DNA, traveling backward through time and seeding itself into history like a virus in the bloodstream of civilization.

He was not the hero who fixed the timeline. He was *the* infection. The one thing that had to happen in 1000 AD for 2150 to exist as it did.

**IX. The Only Way Out**

Jose stood in his room on the 2150 Seville Spire, looking out at the wasteland he had helped create. His body felt wrong—too solid in a world that was becoming energy and ash. He understood now why his left hand had returned functional: the timeline demanded he be able to travel back again.

But if he traveled back, he would repeat the loop. Kill Lupus. Infect the past with 2150 despair. Return to a 2150 that would send him back again.

If he stayed, the *Soulless Rot* consumed humanity completely—no one left to remember him.

The Chrono-Cell sat in the corner, humming with temporal energy. It was waiting for him.

Jose walked to it, his footsteps echoing in the empty room. He opened the panel on his chest and pulled out the memory drive containing the data of 1000 AD. He looked at the image of Lupus’s smiling, dying face.

*“You are the future that needs me to die,”* the monk had said.

Not *I need you to die.*
*You need me to die.*

The future was a closed loop. A snake eating its own tail, and Jose was both the head and the spine.

He inserted the drive into his neural port one last time, then stepped into the Chrono-Cell.

*“This is not a correction,”* he whispered to the empty air, * “It is a completion.”*

The ionic gel swallowed him. He felt his cells unmake themselves again, but this time he did not scream. This time, as he dissolved into backward-flowing time, as the year 2150 faded to blue and then to green and then to stone and candlelight, he did not reach for his weapon.

He reached for Lupus’s hand instead—and this time, when the monk died, Jose would not kill him.

He would let him live. He would carry the *Soulless Rot* back to 2150 without contaminating 1000 AD.

The timeline would reset to its original state: a 2150 where *The Soulless Rot* did not exist, but where Jose Lanz never existed to return and fix it.

He would cease to be the savior and become simply another dead thing in the timeline—a variable erased, a paradox resolved, a ghost who dies twice.

The Chrono-Cell sealed. The hum began.

And in the year 1000 AD, a monk named Lupus looked up from his prayer, felt a sudden chill of grief for a future he had never seen, and continued writing—this time without blood.
